definition.value: A thiouridine in which the oxygen replaced by sulfur is that at C-4.
A cephalosporin compound having acetoxymethyl and [2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino side groups.
Uridine bearing an additional carboxy(hydroxy)methyl substituent at position 5.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is salicylaldehyde in which the hydrogen para- to the hydroxy group is substituted by an amino group.
A hydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of mesalamine, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A uridine having a bromo substituent at the 5-position.
A thiouridine that is 2-thiouridine bearing an additional methoxyaminomethyl substituent at position 5 on the thiouracil ring.
A thiouridine that is 2-thiouridine bearing an additional methoxycarbonylmethyl substituent at position 5 on the thiouracil ring.
A derivative of uridine, bearing an additional methoxycarbonylmethyl substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
A derivative of uridine, bearing an additional methoxy substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
A derivative of uridine, bearing an additional methylaminomethyl substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
Any aminopurine having the amino substituent at the 2-position.
Any compound having 6-aminopurine (adenine) as part of its structure.
A semisynthetic cephamycin antibiotic which, in addition to the methoxy group at the 7alpha position, has 2-thienylacetamido and carbamoyloxymethyl side-groups. It is resistant to beta-lactamase.
The open-chain form of D-glucosamine.
The D-enantiomer of idaric acid.
The D-enantiomer of mannaric acid.
The D-enantiomer of altraric acid.
An amino acid amide that is L-alanine in which the carboxy OH group is replaced by NH2.
The L-enantiomer of erythrose.
Any alpha-amino acid ester that is the ester of L-glutamic acid.
The L-enantiomer of idaric acid.
The L-enantiomer of mannaric acid.

An ornithine derivative resulting from reaction of L-ornithine at the amino group, the carboxy group or the side-chain amino group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-ornithine by a heteroatom.
Altraric acid of L-configuration.
The L-stereoisomer of threose; a major in vivo degradation product of ascorbate.
An alpha-amino acid ester resulting from esterification of the carboxy group of L-tyrosine.
The zwitterionic form of loracarbef.
A N-acyl-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate in which the acyl group specified is acetyl.
An L-amino acid having an N-acetyl substituent.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups and protonation of the amide nitrogen of N-acetyl-L-glutamic acid.
An N-acyl-amino acid that has acetyl as the acyl group.
